Project Requirements:

To meet the GitHub requirements, I used two levels of headers in my repository. The main title, STATS 220, was marked with one header level, while the Projects section and external links section used another level. I emphasised the text explaining the repos purpose using italics. When listing projects under the Projects header, I used ordered lists for project names and unordered lists to provide project descriptions. I also made the project name bold so that the README now had the use of both italics and bold. In order to meet the requirement of using links to other websites, I linked my LinkedIn profile.

My Meme:

My Inspo Meme:

I mainly kept the layout of the meme the same but completely changed the main contents of the meme such as the text (used different fonts and the content of the text was changed) and the images (decided to use cat images I actually find funny).

library(magick)

#Code for my static meme
text1 <- image_blank(width = 400, height = 400, color = "#000000")%>%
  image_annotate(text = "other fonts", color = "#ffffff", size = 50, 
                 font = "Calibri", gravity = "center")

text2 <- image_blank(width = 400, height = 400, color = "#000000")%>%
  image_annotate(text = "comic sans", color = "#ffffff", size = 50, 
                 font = "Comic sans", gravity = "center")


cat <- image_read("cat.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(400)

cool_cat <- image_read("sunglasses cat.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(400)

# First row of the meme
vector1 <- c(text1, cat)
row1 <- image_append(vector1)

# Second row of the meme
vector2 <- c(text2, cool_cat)
row2 <- image_append(vector2)

# Rows put together
rows_vector <- c(row1, row2)
final_meme <- image_append(rows_vector, stack = TRUE)

image_write(final_meme, "my_meme.jpg")

final_meme

library(magick)

# Code for my animated meme

# Using text1, text2, cat and cool_cat from the static meme code
text1 <- image_blank(width = 400, height = 400, color = "#000000")%>%
  image_annotate(text = "other fonts", color = "#ffffff", size = 50, 
                 font = "Calibri", gravity = "center")

text2 <- image_blank(width = 400, height = 400, color = "#000000")%>%
  image_annotate(text = "comic sans", color = "#ffffff", size = 50, 
                 font = "Comic sans", gravity = "center")


cat <- image_read("cat.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(400)

cool_cat <- image_read("sunglasses cat.jpg")%>%
  image_scale(400)

frame1 <- text1
frame2 <- cat
frame3 <- text2
frame4 <- cool_cat

frames <- c(frame1, frame2, frame3, frame4)

meme_gif <- image_animate(frames, fps = 1)

image_write(meme_gif, "my_meme.gif")

Creativity:

My project demonstrates creativity through my use of more CSS than required to improve the appearance of my HTML. I used CSS learnt during lectures to change the colour of the text, the font as well as the font weight of the headings. Then I used additional CSS I learnt outside of class to underline headings in red, add margins and change the colour of links so theyre a different colour when you hover above them.

Learning Reflection:

Some key thing I learnt from Module 1: Creating HTML by combining modern technologies, is how to actually use the R language as well as learning some basics of CSS as I did not have any experience coding in these languages prior to doing this project. It was also my first time using code to actually make/edit visuals so I found it to be a fun new experience. Other things related to data technologies that I am curious about further exploring include data visualisations, as well as further increasing my knowledge of R and CSS. I am interested in learning how R and CSS can combine to actually import and visualise data. I am also curious to learn how to further utilise GitHub for future projects.
